
===== LOGS   =======


✅ 1. Live log (latest, real-time updates)

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport -f

✅ 2. Full log from the beginning

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport

✅ 3. Log from today

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport --since today

✅ 4. Log from last 2 hours

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport --since "2 hours ago"

✅ 5. Log with timestamps and errors only

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport --priority=err

✅ 6. Export log to a file

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport > backend-log.txt

✅ 7. Last mentioned Lines

sudo journalctl -u routing_transport -n 1000 -f







=====    SYSTEMCTL ========



✅ 1. Start the service (after boot or manual restart):

sudo systemctl start routing_transport

✅ 2. Stop the service (if you want to shut it down):

sudo systemctl stop routing_transport

✅ 3. Restart the service (after code/config update):

sudo systemctl restart routing_transport

✅ 4. Check current status (health, errors, etc.):

sudo systemctl status routing_transport

✅ 5. Enable service to auto-start on boot (one-time setup):

sudo systemctl enable routing_transport

✅ 6. Disable auto-start on boot (if needed):

sudo systemctl disable routing_transport

✅ 7. Reload systemd after service file changes (rare):

sudo systemctl daemon-reload




========  NGINX  =================

✅ 1. Start Nginx

sudo systemctl start nginx
.

✅ 2. Stop Nginx

sudo systemctl stop nginx


✅ 3. Restart Nginx

sudo systemctl restart nginx

Restarts Nginx. Use this after:
You update your /etc/nginx/sites-available/ or /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
You make changes to domain mappings or static file paths

✅ 4. Reload Nginx (without full restart)

sudo systemctl reload nginx

Reloads config without killing connections. Use this after minor config changes.

✅ 5. Check Nginx Status

sudo systemctl status nginx
See whether Nginx is active and running.

✅ 6. Enable Nginx to Start on Boot

sudo systemctl enable nginx

✅ 7. Disable Nginx from Starting on Boot

sudo systemctl disable nginx

✅ 8. Test Nginx Configuration (before reload/restart)

sudo nginx -t
Useful after editing /etc/nginx/sites-available/routing_transport.

✅ 9. View Nginx Logs

# Access logs (frontend requests like HTML, JS, CSS, images, etc.)
sudo tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log

# Error logs (404, 502, config errors, etc.)
sudo tail -f /var/log/nginx/error.log

#both logs
sudo tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log /var/log/nginx/error.log







